1
00:00:00,740 --> 00:00:09,243
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambhodassa.

2
00:00:09,263 --> 00:00:13,416
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble, and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:15,067 --> 00:00:21,835
So this little talk is around a discourse called On Upali.

4
00:00:21,856 --> 00:00:25,721
So the Buddha meets this Jain who's called Upali.

5
00:00:25,740 --> 00:00:33,851
And it links in with Last Moon, although it's not necessarily to have listened to the Last Moon one, about Chaitanya, about will.

6
00:00:34,573 --> 00:00:40,567
And what comes first, the body, the mind or speech, you see, in terms of creating karma.

7
00:00:41,130 --> 00:00:48,667
So I'd like to start with the verses that open the Dhammapada, which is this collection of verses by the Buddha.

8
00:00:49,204 --> 00:00:57,621
All experience, all actions are preceded by the mind, led by the mind, made by the mind.

9
00:00:58,362 --> 00:01:06,858
Speak or act with a corrupted mind and suffering follows as the wagon wheel follows the hoof of an ox.

10
00:01:09,319 --> 00:01:15,548
And the opposite, all experience is preceded by mind, led by mind, made by mind.

11
00:01:16,028 --> 00:01:23,897
Speak or act with a peaceful mind or a wholesome mind and happiness follows like a never departing shadow.

12
00:01:25,799 --> 00:01:27,742
Okay, so here we have this discourse.

13
00:01:27,822 --> 00:01:34,551
For those of you who want to know, it's in the Majjhima Nikkai number 56, the Middle Lens Sayings number 56.

14
00:01:35,307 --> 00:01:44,727
So the Buddha is at Nalanda, which was a big town and became a very important university, university town, a big study town.

15
00:01:45,509 --> 00:01:53,585
And at the same time, the Jain leader had turned up with his group of monks and nuns.

16
00:01:54,140 --> 00:02:08,841
And you'll know the Jains, you'll know the big Kumbh Mela that they have every 24 years in India, where, according to this figure, 100 million devotees gathered on the Ganges.

17
00:02:08,905 --> 00:02:16,241
And you've seen those naked ascetics, the Digambaras, they're the sky clad or the space clad.

18
00:02:16,262 --> 00:02:25,141
They are Jain monks, but they've also got a section of Svatambaras, which means they are dressed in white.

19
00:02:26,911 --> 00:02:28,152
So this Jain turns up.

20
00:02:28,173 --> 00:02:31,336
He doesn't say whether he's a digambara or not.

21
00:02:32,318 --> 00:02:37,683
By the way, they're grey because they rub ash into their body, which is an antiseptic.

22
00:02:38,686 --> 00:02:43,191
So this fellow called Diga Tapasin turns up and goes to have a chat with the Buddha.

23
00:02:43,450 --> 00:02:45,794
See, just out of interest.

24
00:02:45,813 --> 00:02:47,956
And he asks the Buddha,

25
00:02:48,729 --> 00:03:01,743
The Buddha asks him, how many actions does the Jain leader Nataputta describe for the making of evil karma, the production of evil karma?

26
00:03:02,872 --> 00:03:11,824
And Tapasin replies, friend Gautama, the Jain, our leader, isn't used to using the word action.

27
00:03:12,324 --> 00:03:14,026
He uses the word rod.

28
00:03:14,646 --> 00:03:20,814
Now, a rod was obviously used as an instrument of punishment, apart from anything else.

29
00:03:21,436 --> 00:03:28,966
And so what the Jain leader was saying was that every time you did something which was unwholesome, you were basically beating yourself.

30
00:03:30,807 --> 00:03:32,811
So he asks, well, how many rods?

31
00:03:33,735 --> 00:03:37,139
does the Jain leader describe?

32
00:03:37,180 --> 00:03:42,727
He says, well, there are three rods, the bodily rod, the verbal rod, and the mental rod.

33
00:03:43,807 --> 00:03:50,575
And is the bodily rod one thing, the verbal rod another, and the mental rod another thing more?

34
00:03:50,896 --> 00:03:53,659
He says, yes, they are all three different things.

35
00:03:54,161 --> 00:03:55,962
All these three rods are

36
00:03:56,281 --> 00:04:18,507
says the Buddha, thus analysed, thus differentiated, which rod does the Nīgānta-nāta-putta, that's his correct name as the Jain leader, describe as the most greatly blameworthy for the making of evil kamma, the production of evil kamma, the bodily rod, the verbal rod, or the mental rod.

37
00:04:18,567 --> 00:04:18,627
And

38
00:04:18,927 --> 00:04:30,538
The Nigantha replies that the bodily rod is the most greatly blameworthy for the making of evil karma, the production of evil karma.

39
00:04:31,180 --> 00:04:35,545
Not so much the verbal rod, not so much the mental rod.

40
00:04:35,584 --> 00:04:43,192
Now you get this little bit of repartee, which it seems in those days, you've got the person to repeat what they said three times.

41
00:04:43,533 --> 00:04:47,297
So they couldn't say, I didn't say that, okay?

42
00:04:47,276 --> 00:04:50,684
So, did you say the bodily rod, diga tapasin?

43
00:04:51,225 --> 00:04:54,572
I say the bodily rod, friend Gotama.

44
00:04:54,593 --> 00:04:57,177
Do you say the bodily rod, diga tapasin?

45
00:04:57,459 --> 00:05:00,966
I say bodily rod, friend Gotama.

46
00:05:00,985 --> 00:05:04,233
Do you say bodily rod, diga tapasin?

47
00:05:04,874 --> 00:05:07,480
I say bodily rod, friend Gotama.

48
00:05:07,459 --> 00:05:13,389
Now, I should think it was just a little bit more repartee like, you know, like, are you sure it's the Bodhi Radha?

49
00:05:13,408 --> 00:05:14,610
I'm absolutely sure.

50
00:05:14,911 --> 00:05:16,273
Is this what your teacher told you?

51
00:05:16,473 --> 00:05:17,555
It is, etc.

52
00:05:18,636 --> 00:05:28,410
So now, having stated his position, Tapasin asks the Buddha, he says, well, what about you, Gautama?

53
00:05:28,971 --> 00:05:30,413
Calls him a friend, Gautama.

54
00:05:31,776 --> 00:05:33,278
How many rods do you describe?

55
00:05:33,778 --> 00:05:38,824
And the Buddha replies that the Tathagata doesn't use the word rod, he uses the word action.

56
00:05:38,925 --> 00:05:39,865
So he says, well, okay.

57
00:05:41,127 --> 00:05:48,153
Which of these actions does the friend Gautama describe as making evil karma the production of karma?

58
00:05:48,595 --> 00:05:53,699
Well, there are three actions, the body, the speech, and the mind.

59
00:05:54,841 --> 00:05:59,927
And is bodily action one thing, verbal action another, mental action another?

60
00:06:00,110 --> 00:06:00,831
Still another.

61
00:06:01,471 --> 00:06:02,894
The Buddha says, yes, this is so.

62
00:06:03,435 --> 00:06:15,716
And of these three actions, thus analysed, thus differentiated, friend Gautama, which action do you describe as the most greatly blameworthy for the making of evil karma, the production of evil karma?

63
00:06:16,257 --> 00:06:19,283
Is it bodily action, verbal action or mental?

64
00:06:20,495 --> 00:06:31,107
And the Buddha replies, of all these threes, it is the mental action which is the most greatly blameworthy for the making of evil karma.

65
00:06:32,329 --> 00:06:34,672
Did you say mental action, friend Gautama?

66
00:06:35,072 --> 00:06:36,372
I said mental action.

67
00:06:36,653 --> 00:06:39,838
Did you say mental action, friend Gautama?

68
00:06:40,257 --> 00:06:42,581
I said mental action, Digha Tapasi.

69
00:06:43,021 --> 00:06:46,105
Are you sure you said mental action, friend Gautama?

70
00:06:46,425 --> 00:06:48,848
I did say mental action.

71
00:06:50,447 --> 00:06:53,153
So at this point, the Jain leaves, right?

72
00:06:53,173 --> 00:06:53,795
He's had enough.

73
00:06:54,136 --> 00:06:55,399
He can't take any more, you see.

74
00:06:56,600 --> 00:07:02,533
And he goes back to the leader, the Jain leader, and he explains what happened.

75
00:07:03,216 --> 00:07:04,598
And the Jain leader praises him.

76
00:07:04,798 --> 00:07:09,468
He says, you've rightly understood the message of the teacher.

77
00:07:10,141 --> 00:07:13,425
And then he makes fun of the Buddha.

78
00:07:13,505 --> 00:07:20,514
He says, what does the trivial mental rod count in comparison to the gross bodily rod?

79
00:07:21,435 --> 00:07:24,961
Anyway, there's a certain Upali who's listening to this.

80
00:07:26,041 --> 00:07:27,103
And he's a householder.

81
00:07:27,764 --> 00:07:35,675
I couldn't quite find out what he did, but he obviously lived in Nalanda and he had some sort of huge mansion because he has servants.

82
00:07:36,495 --> 00:07:39,860
So I'm presuming he's a...

83
00:07:39,942 --> 00:07:46,170
either a landlord or a merchant, because merchants will be coming quite rich at that time.

84
00:07:46,209 --> 00:08:01,971
And he says to Nidhiganta, look, I'm going to go to the Buddha and I'm going to overthrow Gautama, the contemplative teachings on the ground of his position.

85
00:08:02,632 --> 00:08:07,418
And then he gives these wonderful...

86
00:08:07,398 --> 00:08:09,721
similes on how he's going to treat the Buddha.

87
00:08:10,341 --> 00:08:29,687
He says, just as a strong man seizing a long-haired ram by the hair would drag him to and drag him fro and drag him all around in the same way, I, statement by statement, will drag Gautama the contemplative to and drag him fro and drag him all around.

88
00:08:30,249 --> 00:08:36,256
And then he gives more and more sort of similes of how he's going to treat this poor person.

89
00:08:36,236 --> 00:08:39,039
Gautama the Contemplative.

90
00:08:39,059 --> 00:08:39,400
Okay.

91
00:08:41,582 --> 00:08:45,788
So now the Jain leader says, yes, you go and refute his argument, you see.

92
00:08:46,328 --> 00:09:03,948
Now Digha Tapasi says, oh, I'm not so sure this is right that a householder Upali should try that, he says, because Gautama the Contemplative is a magician and he knows a converting magic by which he converts disciples of other sects.

93
00:09:05,029 --> 00:09:05,129
Okay.

94
00:09:05,735 --> 00:09:10,801
So the Buddha has this magic whereby he can convince you that he's right.

95
00:09:12,844 --> 00:09:28,162
By the way, Moggallana, who was one of the two chief disciples, if you remember, Moggallana and Sariputta, he was actually murdered, seemingly, by a sect for converting them, for converting their members to the Buddha Dharma.

96
00:09:28,962 --> 00:09:30,325
He died in Rajgir.

97
00:09:31,105 --> 00:09:34,830
I think it's Rajgir today, yes.

98
00:09:35,265 --> 00:09:37,328
He died just shortly before the Buddha.

99
00:09:39,051 --> 00:09:40,432
He was killed before the Buddha.

100
00:09:44,216 --> 00:09:47,480
Anyway, off he goes.

101
00:09:47,902 --> 00:09:49,123
And he goes off to see the Buddha.

102
00:09:51,385 --> 00:10:01,357
So when he meets the Buddha, the Buddha says to him, if householder, you will confer taking a stand on the truth, we might have a discussion here.

103
00:10:02,317 --> 00:10:05,500
Lord, I will confer to stand on the truth.

104
00:10:05,561 --> 00:10:07,023
Let us have some discussion here.

105
00:10:08,244 --> 00:10:10,726
So what do you think, Householder?

106
00:10:10,748 --> 00:10:23,062
There might be a case where a Negantha, a Jain, is diseased, pained, severely ill, refusing cold water and taking warm water.

107
00:10:23,082 --> 00:10:26,366
He not getting cold water would die.

108
00:10:27,240 --> 00:10:38,418
Where would the leader describe his reappearance?

109
00:10:38,437 --> 00:10:43,065
Now, exactly why he should die, because he doesn't get cold water, there's no explanation for that.

110
00:10:44,567 --> 00:10:51,457
So Upali replies, he would be born amongst the gods attached in mind.

111
00:10:52,078 --> 00:10:53,721
He reappears there.

112
00:10:54,123 --> 00:10:54,943
Why is that?

113
00:10:55,484 --> 00:10:58,226
He is bound by mind when he dies.

114
00:10:59,087 --> 00:11:03,672
So the mental state determines where he will be reborn.

115
00:11:03,932 --> 00:11:06,735
So the Buddha says, oh, householder, pay attention.

116
00:11:07,796 --> 00:11:10,198
Answer only after having paid attention.

117
00:11:11,120 --> 00:11:24,011
What you said after isn't consistent with what you said before, nor is what you said after consistent with what you said before, what is consistent with what you said after.

118
00:11:25,087 --> 00:11:27,599
So there's a little bit of argy-bargy there.

119
00:11:28,260 --> 00:11:31,234
And then he gives him a second example.

120
00:11:31,365 --> 00:11:36,831
There might be a case where an Agantha is constrained by the fourfold constraints.

121
00:11:37,732 --> 00:11:47,724
So this is the four precepts of not harming, not stealing, not being unchaste and lying.

122
00:11:48,784 --> 00:11:51,828
And then he says constrained by all the constraints.

123
00:11:51,869 --> 00:11:56,614
So this is all the rules and regulations of the order of James.

124
00:11:57,725 --> 00:12:02,793
And as he walks to and fro, he brings many small beings to destruction.

125
00:12:03,875 --> 00:12:09,202
What karmic result would the Jain leader describe for him?

126
00:12:10,745 --> 00:12:17,635
What is unintended, Lord, the Nigantha Nataputta does not describe as greatly blameworthy.

127
00:12:18,677 --> 00:12:23,125
But if he intends it, asks the Buddha, greatly blameworthy, Lord.

128
00:12:23,932 --> 00:12:28,618
And under what does the Nīgānta-nātaputta classify intention?

129
00:12:29,599 --> 00:12:30,821
Under the mental rod.

130
00:12:32,543 --> 00:12:34,605
Householder, pay attention.

131
00:12:35,365 --> 00:12:37,369
Answer after having paid attention.

132
00:12:37,990 --> 00:12:46,259
What you said after isn't consistent with what you said before, nor what is what you said before consistent with what you said after.

133
00:12:46,476 --> 00:12:51,528
Okay, so then he gives a couple of examples, which are a bit difficult for us.

134
00:12:51,807 --> 00:13:01,227
So he asks Supali, for instance, if a man with a sword were to go into Nalanda, would he be able to kill everybody in that city?

135
00:13:01,546 --> 00:13:04,110
And Upali says, no, this is not possible.

136
00:13:04,510 --> 00:13:11,884
He said, but supposing he had through the power of mind, through the mastery of mind, superhuman power, could he do it then?

137
00:13:12,644 --> 00:13:14,268
So Upali said, yes, he could.

138
00:13:14,607 --> 00:13:21,360
So then he said, ah, see what comes first in terms of importance, the mind or the body?

139
00:13:22,554 --> 00:13:26,730
So he gives another example about wildernesses, which we don't need to go into.

140
00:13:27,393 --> 00:13:32,312
Anyway, with the last example, Upali gives in and he confesses.

141
00:13:32,495 --> 00:13:38,985
Lord, I was gratified and won over by the Blessed One's first simile.

142
00:13:39,686 --> 00:13:48,659
But wanting to hear these very artful ways of handling questions from the Blessed One, I thought I should treat him as an opponent.

143
00:13:49,761 --> 00:13:55,971
Magnificent, Lord, magnificent, just as if he were to place upright what was overturned.

144
00:13:56,339 --> 00:14:05,726
to reveal what was hidden, to show the way to one who was lost, or to carry a lamp into the dark so that those with eyes could see forms.

145
00:14:06,128 --> 00:14:12,033
In this way, the Blessed One, through many lines of reasoning, made the Dharma clear.

146
00:14:12,052 --> 00:14:16,197
I go to the Blessed One for refuge, to the Dharma, to the Sangha.

147
00:14:16,437 --> 00:14:26,346
May the Blessed One remember me as a lay follower who has gone forth to Him for refuge from this day forward for life.

148
00:14:26,326 --> 00:14:36,976
Well, the next thing the Buddha said really impresses Upal because he says, look, make a careful scrutiny householder.

149
00:14:37,736 --> 00:14:43,283
It is good for well-known people like yourself to make careful scrutiny.

150
00:14:43,623 --> 00:14:49,688
In other words, don't make up your mind until you've delved a little more into the teachings.

151
00:14:49,708 --> 00:14:51,211
Now this impresses him.

152
00:14:51,230 --> 00:14:55,674
But the next one is even more impressive, seemingly for that time.

153
00:14:55,654 --> 00:15:10,197
Householder, your family compound has long been like a waterhole for the Jains, and you should consider that alms food should be given to them when they come for it.

154
00:15:11,399 --> 00:15:22,336
Now, there's an occasion in the scriptures where the Buddhist monks and nuns are in the shrine, these big parks where they had these shrines.

155
00:15:22,519 --> 00:15:26,505
And there's lots of food left over after the lay people have offered.

156
00:15:27,125 --> 00:15:30,751
And so Ananda says to the Buddha, you know, what should we do with all this food?

157
00:15:31,152 --> 00:15:34,956
He says, well, offer it to these other sects, you see.

158
00:15:35,658 --> 00:15:37,922
But when the lay people heard this, they were very angry.

159
00:15:38,121 --> 00:15:40,085
We don't feed people who are Jains.

160
00:15:40,125 --> 00:15:40,926
We don't do that.

161
00:15:40,946 --> 00:15:42,288
You know, we fed you.

162
00:15:42,368 --> 00:15:45,172
We don't want you to feed them with our food.

163
00:15:45,672 --> 00:15:51,801
So there's a rule, you know, I can't offer food or a cup of tea to a priest.

164
00:15:52,017 --> 00:15:56,942
or to a Muslim mullah or anybody who belongs to another sect.

165
00:15:58,284 --> 00:15:59,767
So that's how it was in those days.

166
00:15:59,787 --> 00:16:07,476
So this obviously impresses Upali that the Buddha should say, look, you should continue to feed the Jains.

167
00:16:08,918 --> 00:16:14,346
So then the Buddha gives him what's known as the graduated talk.

168
00:16:14,511 --> 00:16:16,234
He talks about generosity.

169
00:16:16,735 --> 00:16:18,317
He talks about virtue.

170
00:16:18,878 --> 00:16:24,785
He talks about what happens when you die with the virtuous, generous heart, you're born into a heavenly place.

171
00:16:25,886 --> 00:16:33,076
He then talks about the drawbacks of being devoted to sensuality and the rewards of renunciation.

172
00:16:34,288 --> 00:17:00,854
And then, when the householder was of ready mind, malleable mind, unhindered mind, exultant mind, confident mind, he proclaimed to him the distinctive teaching of the awakened ones, suffering, the cause of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the path leading to the cessation of suffering.

173
00:17:01,394 --> 00:17:02,676
And right there,

174
00:17:03,128 --> 00:17:15,969
there arose in Upali, the householder, in that very seat, the dustless, stainless Dharma eye, whatever is subject to arising is subject to disappearing.

175
00:17:16,128 --> 00:17:29,912
In other words, he saw impermanence deep enough for him to become a stream entrance, which is the first rung of awakening.

176
00:17:32,423 --> 00:17:34,026
So now he's very happy.

177
00:17:34,046 --> 00:17:34,826
He goes home.

178
00:17:35,488 --> 00:17:40,557
And of course, the news gets back to the Nigantha, to the Jain leader.

179
00:17:40,656 --> 00:17:42,840
Upali has now become a disciple of the Buddha.

180
00:17:43,060 --> 00:17:44,083
Well, he can't believe it.

181
00:17:44,222 --> 00:17:45,746
You know, it's not possible.

182
00:17:45,806 --> 00:17:49,352
So off he goes to see Upali.

183
00:17:50,512 --> 00:17:58,599
And he gets to the household and Upali has told his gatekeeper not to let them in.

184
00:17:59,180 --> 00:18:07,928
So Upali, so the Neganthus says to the gatekeeper, look, you go and tell Upali that I'm here and I want to talk to him.

185
00:18:08,887 --> 00:18:14,472
So eventually he gives in and he arranges the middle gate hall.

186
00:18:14,492 --> 00:18:20,317
So I presume that there was a wall around the gate

187
00:18:20,804 --> 00:18:23,227
mansion or whatever he had, this large place.

188
00:18:23,946 --> 00:18:33,498
And you came in and there was some sort of sheltered place where I would presume mendicants were invited in and fed.

189
00:18:34,138 --> 00:18:38,323
And in it, there would be a seat, a proper high seat for the leader.

190
00:18:40,665 --> 00:18:42,428
Well, he takes the high seat.

191
00:18:42,567 --> 00:18:48,094
Upali takes the high seat and the Neganthas come in, the Jains come in, you see.

192
00:18:48,866 --> 00:18:53,971
And this is what he says to Pali, the householder.

193
00:18:53,991 --> 00:18:55,432
You've gone mad, householder.

194
00:18:55,753 --> 00:18:56,934
You're an arrogant fool.

195
00:18:57,635 --> 00:19:06,585
Having gone saying, Lord, I am going, I will overthrow Gotham of the contemplative's teachings, you've come back tied up in a web of his doctrine.

196
00:19:07,125 --> 00:19:13,191
It's just as if a man, having gone to remove someone else's testicles, comes back with his own removed.

197
00:19:14,571 --> 00:19:16,173
That's good, isn't it?

198
00:19:16,913 --> 00:19:22,980
Or is it that if a man, having gone to gouge somebody else's eyes out, comes back with his own gouged out?

199
00:19:23,621 --> 00:19:32,432
In the same way, having gone saying, Lord, I am going to overthrow Gautama the contemplative's teachings, you've come back tied up in the web of his doctrine.

200
00:19:32,792 --> 00:19:39,681
You've been converted, householder, by Gautama the contemplative's converting magic.

201
00:19:40,775 --> 00:19:46,742
And Upali replies, oh, auspicious, venerable sir, is the converting magic.

202
00:19:47,284 --> 00:19:51,229
Admirable, venerable sir, is the converting magic.

203
00:19:52,029 --> 00:20:01,702
And seemingly then, the Jain leader gets so upset, he spews blood, it seems, or something like that.

204
00:20:01,935 --> 00:20:11,321
And so they leave, and there's an occasion here where Upali goes on to create this lovely PM to the Buddha, these lovely...

205
00:20:11,520 --> 00:20:14,003
verses in which he praises the Buddha.

206
00:20:14,703 --> 00:20:25,355
So, this whole story is really coming back to this position that the Buddha says that nothing happens unless it's, first of all, happened in the mind.

207
00:20:26,256 --> 00:20:38,388
And it's within the mind that we have this will, this cetana, and it's these decisions that we make that produce our actions, in this case, unwholesome actions,

208
00:20:38,368 --> 00:20:39,830
It all begins in the mind.

209
00:20:40,230 --> 00:20:55,729
So as soon as we're aware of something in the mind which is unwholesome and we sort of allow it to arise and pass away, then it cannot express itself through our words, through our speech and through our actions.

210
00:20:57,351 --> 00:21:05,220
So I would just like to finish by repeating again those opening discourse, those opening verses from the Dhammapada.

211
00:21:08,136 --> 00:21:15,065
All experience or actions is preceded by mind, led by mind, made by mind.

212
00:21:15,645 --> 00:21:23,434
Speak or act with a corrupted mind and suffering follows as the wagon wheel follows the hoof of the ox.

213
00:21:24,616 --> 00:21:30,443
All experience is preceded by mind, led by mind, made by mind.

214
00:21:31,144 --> 00:21:37,231
Speak or act with a peaceful mind, wholesome mind, and happiness follows like a never ending.

215
00:21:37,549 --> 00:21:40,193
departing shadows.

216
00:21:40,213 --> 00:21:55,557
I can only hope my little discourse has been of some assistance, that it does not cause confusion, and that by your practice of the Dharma you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

